:::: {.cr-section layout="overlay-center"}

Investments in infrastructure are often packaged with promises of local economic development. @cr-ikeSigning

The **Federal-Aid Highway Act of 1956** launched the largest public infrastructure project in US history. The act made way for the 41,000-mile network of freeways that reshaped regional connectivity. @cr-ikeSigning

Did counties that gained access to the Interstate Highway System experience stronger employment growth? @cr-ikeSigning

Put differently, imagine there are two identical counties but, for some reason, only one of them gained Interstate access. Would **employment growth** be different between those counties? @cr-ikeSigning

Of course, because routes were directed through already dense and developing areas, correlations between Interstate access and growth contain **selection bias**.  @cr-ikeSigning

In this project, I introduce a new research design to identify the **causal impact** of counties' Interstate access on long-term employment growth. @cr-ikeSigning

::: {#cr-ikeSigning}
![](images/ikeSigning.jpg){width="60%" fig-align="center"}
:::
::::


:::: {.cr-section layout="overlay-right"}
Frye assembles county-level employment data by integrating Census records from multiple sources @cr-empLevels.

I classify counties within 25 km of an Interstate highway as the 'treatment group'. Black points depict the treatment group’s average employment; gray points represent all other counties @cr-empLevels.

Counties with Interstate access experience exponential employment growth! However, these counties began with higher baseline employment and, possibly, were already growing faster @cr-empLevels.

::: {#cr-empLevels}
![](images/rawGrowthRates/empLevels.jpeg){width="40%" style="margin-left: 10px; display: block; margin-right: auto;"}
:::
::::

### Given this exponential divergence, let's consider this regression specification:

:::: {.cr-section layout="sidebar-right"}

For every year, I take a log approximation of employment growth since 1953... [@cr-regressionEquation]{highlight="cr-logEmpChange_reg"}

...and regress it on an Interstate access 'treatment group' indicator... [@cr-regressionEquation]{highlight="cr-treatment_reg"}

...while controlling for pre-Interstate baseline characteristics. [@cr-regressionEquation]{highlight="cr-controls_reg"}

<!-- Conley standard errors are used to account for spatial autocorrelation. [@cr-regressionEquation]{highlight="cr-error_reg"} -->

Due to the selection bias, OLS estimates of $\beta_{1}$ are probably larger than the causal effect. So, I construct a novel instrumental variable to instrument for the treatment. [@cr-regressionEquation]{highlight="cr-beta_reg"}

In other words, I am looking for a variable that helps predict which counties received Interstate access. [@cr-regressionEquation]{highlight="cr-treatment_reg"}

But, to correct for the selection bias, it should be unrelated to location fundamentals and unobserved forces that shape how these counties’ labor markets evolve. [@cr-regressionEquation]{highlight="cr-error_reg"}


::: {#cr-regressionEquation style="font-size: 1.5em;"}
| [$\log(Y_{c,t}) - \log(Y_{c,1953})$]{#cr-logEmpChange_reg} $= \beta_{0} +$ [$\beta_{1}$]{#cr-beta_reg} [$\text{Treatment}_{c}$]{#cr-treatment_reg} $+ \,$ [$X_{c}$]{#cr-controls_reg} $\gamma + \,$ [$\varepsilon_{c}$]{#cr-error_reg}
:::
::::


